[3] Brazil (Minas Gerais)
Date: Sun 8 Feb 2008
Source: Jornal Hoje em Dia [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.hojeemdia.com.br/v2/busca/index.php?sessao=10&data_edicao_anterior=2009-02-06&ver=1Â¬icia=8768>



Coronel Fabriciano, the city with the 3rd highest rate of infestation of
_Aedes aegypti_ in Minas Gerais state (6.9 per cent [house infestation
rate]), added 2 deaths of suspected DHF (dengue hemorrhagic fever), causing
the Municipality of Coronel Fabriciano to take more energetic measures to
contain a possible epidemic. The betting is on homeopathy. Joint efforts
will be made starting tomorrow, across the city, so that the population of
about 105 000 inhabitants, take without charge the 2 drops of a homeopathic
remedy that promises to decrease the body's susceptibility to dengue [virus
infection], and mitigate the effects of the disease.

The novel [treatment] comes from the city of Macae (Rio de Janeiro),
[carried out at] the hands of homeopath and medical coordinator of the
Public Health of the Municipality of that city, Leila Nunes. According to
specialists, while the neighboring cities recorded up to a 300 per cent
increase of the disease, Macae had a significant reduction in its [dengue]
indices. "After distributing the product, reported dengue cases were
reduced by up to 65 per cent in 2008, compared to the previous year [2007].
In the 1st 3 months of 2008, compared with the same period of 2007, the
rate of dengue cases fell by 93 per cent. We started the application [of
the drug] in the population during the peak of the epidemic. We noticed the
drop in cases that still occurred that year [2008], but was much more
abrupt than in years earlier," said the doctor. The medicine helps to
reduce bleeding. The remedy consists of 3 substances: phosphorus,
_Eupatorium_, a North American plant, and extract of _Crotalus horridus_
rattlesnake venom.

"We created a volunteer cleanup force, for "project clean up stuff",
[public] awareness campaigns, and the dial-dengue [information telephone
line]. We have more health workers than recommended by the Ministry Health
and most recently passed a law authorizing the city government to impose
fines of BRL 680 to BRL 1380 [USD 300-609] for people who do not cooperate
in the elimination the focus [breeding sites] of _Aedes aegypti_. Still,
the index of infestation is high. Lack of awareness in the population and
this will take time to change. Dengue in Fabriciano may worsen still
further, " concluded Chico Simoes, prefect of the city.

The advice of the State Secretariat of Health reported to the municipal
departments is that they have autonomy to adopt solutions or measures they
consider best suited to resolve their issues.

Military Armed Forces will also tackle the mosquito transmits dengue
[virus] in the state. Today [8 Feb 2009] ends the training course given by
the state Secretariat for 100 soldiers of the 12th Infantry Battalion (IB)
of Belo Horizonte. Another 200 soldiers will be trained in next 2 weeks to
participate in activities in the region or in other cities in the state.
The participation of the Armed Forces to fight _Aedes aegypti_ was through
an agreement between the Ministries of Health and Defense. The idea is to
train 2000 soldiers in Brazil.

This 1st group of soldiers must act initially intersectorially in the 9
regions of the Belo Horizonte prefecture and in surrounding towns that have
registered large numbers of mosquito infestations or that have few staff
for health and zoonoses control [available] to make visits and to combat
outbreaks. In training, the military were introduced to [diflubenzuron], a
new insecticide that will be adopted, that is more effective and less toxic.

[byline: Gabriel Pascoal]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report asserts that the homeopathic treatment reduces incidence of
dengue disease and is aimed at reducing hemorrhage. The cited example of
use in Macae city is anecdotal. Unfortunately, there is no satisfactory
animal model for dengue to test this treatment experimentally. A
well-designed double-blind drug/placebo field trial would be required to
make a convincing case for the efficacy and safety of this treatment.

Dengue is a serious problem in Coronel Fabriciano city. The UAI of 4 Feb
2009 (in Portuguese,
<http://www.uai.com.br/UAI/html/sessao_2/2009/02/04/em_noticia_interna,id_sessao=2&id_noticia=97917/em_noticia_interna.shtml>,
cited by ProMED-PORT, indicated that just in January 2009, there were 257
reported suspected cases of dengue. Throughout 2008 there were 1596 cases.
According to the director of Siderurgica Hospital, Marcos Vinicius da Silva
Bizarro, the situation in the city is worrying. The hospital attends more
than 20 suspected cases of dengue daily.

Dengue is also a problem in Belo Horizonte, the capital of Minas Gerais. G1
of 4 Feb 2009 (in Portuguese,
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Brasil/0,,MUL986486-5598,00-DENGUE+TIPO+DEIXA+PREFEITURA+DE+BELO+HORIZONTE+EM+ALERTA.html>
reported that dengue virus 2 is circulating in the city, which has now been
placed on alert. As of 2 Feb 2009 there have been 42 confirmed dengue cases.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Minas
Gerais and other states can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-10.8,-53.1,4>. - Mod.TY]

