[4] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Tue 3 Feb 2009
Source: So Noticias, A Gazeta report [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.sonoticias.com.br/mostra.php?id=82034>


The mayor of Rosario Oeste (128 km/80 mi north of Cuiaba), Jose Joemil
Balduino de Araujo, asked the government to declare a state of emergency in
the city because of an outbreak of dengue. Between December 2008 and
January this year [2009] there were 226 reported cases of the disease. Of
these, 19 were confirmed as dengue fever and 3 as the most severe DHF,
which can kill, while another 3 cases of this type are being analyzed.

Rosario Oeste has about 18 000 inhabitants. According to the coordinator of
Epidemiology of the Municipal Secretariat of Health, Maria da Penha de
Jesus, the reports that are released by the 9 districts of the city, are of
even more concern, because they do not indicate that these are isolated cases.

To avoid the picture becoming even more critical, a serological survey was
made in the neighborhoods, to detect which type of virus is circulating in
municipality. The result should l be available in 20 days and will allow
isolation [of virus? Quarantine? - Mod.TY], if necessary.

In 2005 and 2006, Rosario Oeste had its 1st [dengue] outbreak, with 218
reported cases of classical dengue fever, a number that has already been
exceeded currently. Because of this, the concern is the risk of recurrence
of disease in people who have had dengue in the past. When a person has a
dengue [virus infection] for the 2nd time, there is a risk of having
hemorrhage.

The coordinator considers that the public had become used to a period of
[dengue] tranquility in 2007, when there were not a high number of recorded
dengue [cases] in the city. This, in his opinion, diminished preventive
actions in 2008.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Even if we consider only the confirmed cases, 21, we have a monthly
incidence of 50 cases per 100 000 inhabitants (the city is about 20 000
