[5] Brazil (Acre)
Date: Sat 7 Feb 2009
Source: Pagina 20 [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.pagina20.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4081&Itemid=14>


The Secretariat for Health of the state of Acre (SESACRE) announced
yesterday afternoon [6 Feb 2009] the 1st death caused by DHF in the state
in 2009. The victim was 31 years old and was resident of the 6 de Agosto
neighborhood. The case was among 11 that were under investigation by the
Municipal Secretariat of Health (SEMSA) -- 3 of these have been discarded
and 8 are still under clinical and medical evaluation.

According to the deputy secretary of health, Thor Dantas, the cases where
there is suspected [dengue] disease the [care givers] are examined by the
medical team of the Secretariat and the patients do not exhibit severe
[dengue] symptoms. "It is with much regret that announce the loss. The
victim died in the emergency unit but received all necessary assistance.
For the other cases, we are optimistic in relation to the manifestations of
the disease, the treatment for which is evolving, without serious damage to
the health of these patients," he said.

He ensures that the health and epidemiological surveillance of SEMSA is
gathering all the data to define the diagnosis these patients. "All the
clinical tests are being performed. We are treating the matter very
seriously and respecting the people. We still have 2 months of rain and our
work must be further intensified," he said.

The population in the [state] capital has 3 centers of specialized care for
cases of dengue, as well as a task force that serves to combat the mosquito
_Aedes aegypti_. "We will determine the need to open an additional health
center for cases of dengue, and in this analysis we recognize the work of
the people, the government teams, municipality, and entity partners that
are working hard on the destruction of the mosquito breeding sites. Without
such action, we believe that we will be facing a even worse situation,
because fighting a disease [virus] caused by a mosquito [vector
transmission] in the Amazon region is too great a challenge," he declared.

The municipal secretary of health, Pascal Khalil, said that all cases are
being detected where they originate, thereby detecting all neighborhoods
with foci of the disease. "The neighborhoods that are receiving priority
action by epidemic health agents and other volunteers and partners, such as
Conquista, Estacao Experimental, Placas, Taquari, Mocinha Magalhaes, and
Esperanca, are those with the largest number of cases reported with
suspected [dengue] disease," he emphasized.

According to the secretaries, the efforts against spread of disease will be
reinforced in the months of February, March and April, with total funds
available from the state to strengthen the actions to combat dengue.

[byline: Lyslane Mendes]

