[6] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Fri 6 Feb 2009
Source: Correio [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://correio24horas.globo.com/noticias/noticia.asp?codigo=18060&mdl=50>


Children up to 9 years of age account for almost 70 per cent of dengue in
Itabuna, Jequie, and Porto Seguro. The worst situation is in Porto Seguro,
where 2 children have died because of disease and Itabuna where 6 children
are hospitalized daily with symptoms of the disease.

According to Sabrina Menezes, a technician of Epidemiological Surveillance
of Porto Seguro, of the 74 cases reported in 2009, 60 per cent are
children. Samples tested by the municipal laboratory have now confirmed 36
[as dengue cases].

In Itabuna, the situation is also considered alarming. As of the 3rd week
January [2009], 131 people had been hospitalized with suspected dengue, 3
with DHF, with 80 per cent of the total being children between 2-9 years.
According to Antonio Vieira, secretary of health of the city, there was a
fatal case of dengue -- serotype 2, a child of 4 years, last week in the
Maria da Penha neighborhood, that is being studied by LACEN (Central
Laboratory). Moreover, in the 3 city hospitals that serve children, there
are 6-8 new admissions per day.

The municipality of Jequie is experiencing an outbreak of the disease since
early this year [2009]. Besides the death of a boy of 7 years, 2700 cases
of the disease have been reported in the city (which is more than 64.4 per
cent of all reported [cases] in the state this year).

Outbreaks of the disease in Itabuna are concentrated in 4 peripheral
neighborhoods in the city (Sao Caetano, Urbis 4, Sandoval Palmeira, and
California). According to Menezes Sandovaldo Carvalho, city coordinator to
combat dengue, 80 per cent of [mosquito] breeding sites are
intra-domiciliary (majority in the [house and] yard) and only 20 per cent
are in vacant lots and abandoned buildings. Because of this, the city is
studying the possibility of following the example of Cuba, where the
population was fined where mosquito [breeding sites] were found in houses.

Unlike other cities, in Barreiras -- west of the state -- children account
for only 16 per cent of cases of the disease. In the municipality, 98 cases
were reported in 2009, of these, there is now one confirmed case of DHF in
a child of 7 years -- and 2 of classical [dengue], according to Alline
Santana Lima, of Epidemiological Surveillance of Barreiras.

According to SESAB this (2009) there have been 1955 reported cases of
classic dengue. Of these, 48 were in the capital. The worst situation is in
Jequie, which has 64.4 per cent of the cases of the state with 1247. DHF
was recorded in 12 people (5 in Jequie, 1 each in Apuarema, Barrieras,
Camacari, Castro Alves, Itabuna, Manoel Vitorino, and Salvador).

[byline: Jorge Gauthier]
--

communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Jequie has about 150 inhabitants, this results in an incidence rate of
about 1800 cases per 100 000 inhabitants, epidemic that nobody can deny.
For a long time, this moderator has warned that dengue in Brazil would,
gradually, become more severe and present greater incidence in children.
Unfortunately, it is what we are seeing. - Mod.LJS]

