[8] Bolivia
Date: Mon 9 Feb 2009
Source: Globovision.com [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.globovision.com/news.php?nid=109710>


Bolivia reports 1000 new dengue cases per day, in the most serious epidemic
of the last decade, which has left 5 people dead and more than 12 000
individuals infected, reported the Ministry of Health, cited this Saturday
[7 Feb 2009] in the local press.

According to the latest medical report from the Ministry of Health, up
until Friday [6 Feb 2009], 12 2372 cases of classical dengue have been
reported, of which 75 per cent are recorded in the tropical department
[state of province equivalent] of Santa Cruz (eastern [Bolivia]), with 8200
reported up to Tuesday [3 Feb 2009].

The medical report signals that in the 9 departments in Bolivia, dengue
illnesses reported are: 9306 in Santa Cruz (eastern [Bolivia]), 820 in Beni
(north east), 738 in Cochabamba (central), 492 in Tarija (south), 460 in
Pando (north), 229 in Chuquisaca (south east) 283 in La Paz (east), 35 in
Oruro, and 9 en Potosi.

The national director of epidemiology, Juan Carlos Arraya, indicated on
Friday [6 Feb 2009], "When we reach the peak of the epidemic we could have
more than 50 000 [dengue] cases in the entire country, without including
the sick individuals who do not report to the medical authorities."

The government has declared a "health emergency' in the departments of
Santa Cruz, Beni, Pando and Cochabamba, where the greatest number of cases
have been reported.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The dengue epidemic in tropical, lowland Bolivia is clearly out of
control, despite the attempts at mosquito vector control by the Bolivian
army and health brigades. In its 9 Feb 2009 edition, the El Informador (in
Spanish,
<http://www.informador.com.mx/internacional/2009/77033/6/afecta-dengue-a-mas-de-11-mil-personas-en-bolivia.htm>)
reported that the Santa Cruz hospitals have collapsed under the pressure of
the dengue patients that have been attended to.

A map showing the departments mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_admin_2006.jpg>. A
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Bolivia can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-16.7,-64.7,5>. - Mod.TY]

